  "ADUs": {
    "ADU1": {
      "text": "The aim of this article is to draw interest to a period, or rather a certain philosophical culture, which has been neglected so far by standard historians of philosophy.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU2": {
      "text": "Until recently Francisco Suárez (1548-1617) has been regarded as representing the climax of these scholastic discussions.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU3": {
      "text": "In fact, however, Suárez stood at the beginning, rather than at the end, of an interesting and highly sophisticated philosophical culture, flourishing from 1597 (the year of the publication of Suárez's Metaphysical Disputations) until around 1700.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU4": {
      "text": "This culture should best be called 'Baroque scholasticism.'",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU5": {
      "text": "I offer some ideas on why the study of the period has been until recently neglected and argue that more attention should be paid to it.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU6": {
      "text": "It is a known fact that the scholastic tradition flourished in the West in the medieval period, but in reality it continued well into the Renaissance and the Baroque.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU7": {
      "text": "Unfortunately, it is hard to detect this fact from today's standard historiography written in English.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU8": {
      "text": "With the exception of Suárez (and perhaps John of St. Thomas), seventeenth-century scholasticism seems still a virtually uncharted territory.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU9": {
      "text": "This article is divided into four parts.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU10": {
      "text": "The first argues that seventeenth-century scholasticism should be best labeled 'Baroque scholasticism' (I).",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU11": {
      "text": "The second presents a brief account of its emergence (II).",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU12": {
      "text": "The third argues that this period should be viewed as a sui generis chapter in the history of ideas (III).",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU13": {
      "text": "The fourth gives reasons for its investigation (IV).",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU14": {
      "text": "Although the article provides some information about Baroque scholastic culture, it is not intended to be a short history of Baroque scholasticism.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU15": {
      "text": "The article offers only preliminary and general considerations of Baroque scholasticism, without treating in depth any particular Baroque author or topic.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU16": {
      "text": "Contemporary and future historians need to undertake many specialized studies in order to be able eventually to come up with a reliable and philosophically illuminating outline of the period.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU17": {
      "text": "At the moment it is premature to attempt such an outline.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU18": {
      "text": "Finally, although in my opinion Baroque philosophical culture is valuable not just for historians but also from the systematic point of view, this claim will not be substantiated in an article such as this, which deals primarily with historical considerations.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU19": {
      "text": "In the seventeenth century, an 'alternative' philosophical culture runs parallel to the well-known culture of so-called 'modern philosophy,' which is usually 'presented as a contest between two philosophies - Cartesian rationalism and British empiricism.'",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU20": {
      "text": "This culture had its own agenda (which was, however, not entirely dissimilar to the agenda of 'modern philosophy'), a standard set of assumptions, and its own technical language and methods.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU21": {
      "text": "Both in the Protestant and Catholic parts of Europe and the Americas, it was at home in universities, seminaries and other institutions of higher learning and it was 'the mainstream philosophy of the time.'",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU22": {
      "text": "The roots of this culture lie in the Middle Ages but many new elements had been integrated into it during the Renaissance.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU23": {
      "text": "This culture reached its peak between 1630 and 1680 and it was still alive in the mid-eighteenth century, in the works of such authors as Luis de Losada (1681-1748).",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU24": {
      "text": "Historians of philosophy use various labels to refer to this culture.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU25": {
      "text": "Some of these labels, such as 'late medieval,' 'Renaissance,' 'early modern Aristotelianism/scholasticism,' are inaccurate, whereas others, such as 'Second scholastic,' 'Counter-Reformation philosophy,' might carry unwelcome connotations.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU26": {
      "text": "My suggestion is to call this culture Baroque scholasticism and take it to be the successor of Renaissance scholasticism, both being phases of Postmedieval scholasticism.",
      "label": "claim"
    }
  },
